---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Icon from '../components/Icon.astro';

// DRAFT front page — stood up at /pattern for review, unlinked from nav.
// Built from the ruled Section-2 spine (drafts/frontpage_section2_spine_r1.md)
// plus the ruled recognition-cascade and DDJ-reveal material. Not yet the homepage.
---

<BaseLayout title="The Pattern">
  <article class="max-w-2xl mx-auto" style="font-family: var(--font-body);">

    <!-- ============ 1 · Hook + the one bet ============ -->
    <header class="mb-16">
      <p class="text-lg themed-text-secondary mb-6">This began with a question I couldn't put down:</p>
      <p class="text-2xl italic mb-8" style="color: var(--color-text); line-height: 1.4;">
        If reality is truly infinite, how does that actually work?
      </p>
      <p class="themed-text-secondary mb-4" style="line-height: var(--leading-prose);">
        Not infinite as a figure of speech. Not "really, really big." Genuinely, structurally
        infinite — infinitely vast <em>and</em> infinitely divisible: no largest thing, no
        smallest, no edge, no floor, no bottom to reach in either direction.
      </p>
      <p class="themed-text-secondary" style="line-height: var(--leading-prose);">
        I can't prove reality is like that — nobody can, in either direction. So this is the one
        thing I'll ask you to grant, and the only one. Grant it, and everything that follows is
        just logic — watch it go. Refuse it, and there's nothing here to argue about; we part ways
        at the door, no hard feelings. Everything past this line stands or falls on that single
        <em>if</em>.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="themed-border border-t mb-16"></div>

    <!-- ============ 2 · The logic falls out ============ -->
    <section class="mb-16 space-y-6 themed-text-secondary" style="line-height: var(--leading-prose);">
      <p>
        Start with something almost too simple to notice: for anything to <em>be</em> something,
        there has to be something it <em>isn't</em>. A thing with no edge, no difference, nothing
        it's not — that isn't a thing. It's not even there. To exist at all is to be
        distinguishable from something else.
      </p>
      <p>
        Now push the two together. Picture the two extremes. A perfect <em>nothing</em> —
        everything divided away until nothing's left. And a perfect <em>everything</em> — all
        difference collapsed into one undivided whole. Both are states with no distinction left in
        them. And we just said no-distinction can't exist. So the extremes aren't rare, or far
        away. They're <em>impossible</em> — not places you haven't reached, but conditions that
        can't hold together. And infinity is exactly what keeps you from ever arriving at either:
        you can always divide once more, so you never bottom out into pure emptiness; there's
        always more beyond the edge, so you never close into pure fullness.
      </p>
      <p>
        Here's the turn. Reality is <em>here</em> — you're reading this. It isn't the impossible
        extreme, and it isn't nothing. So distinction obtains. Not switched on, not begun — there's
        no "before" for it to begin from, and no moment when a switch was thrown. Its absence is
        simply never available: absolute sameness can't cohere — not anywhere, not at any scale,
        not ever. Distinction has always obtained, obtains now, and always will — not because
        anything made it, but because the alternative was never a possibility. It doesn't begin. It
        holds.
      </p>
      <p>
        And a distinction is never one-sided. <em>This</em> has no meaning without <em>not-this</em>
        — they hold each other up, each the measure of the other, so that more of one is exactly
        less of the other. That reciprocal relation <em>is</em> a gradient: the whole range from
        all-one-side to all-the-other, with a place where the two stand equal, and a center where
        they would coincide and cancel. None of it is added on afterward. To have a difference at
        all is already to have the whole of it — two poles, a gradient, a balance, a center. Not
        built in steps. One structure, read in parts.
      </p>
      <p>
        Now watch what that center is. It's the place where the two sides perfectly cancel — where
        all distinction goes to zero. But that's the very thing we just said can't exist. So the
        center of every structure is the one point the structure can never actually reach. Try to
        get there and it recedes: like compressing a spring toward its core, the coils crowd
        infinitely closer and the collapse never finishes. There's always another coil between you
        and the center. It's an asymptote, not a destination — it shapes every approach, and the
        meeting never arrives.
      </p>
      <p>
        So you can't rest at the center — and you can't cross it either; there's no <em>there</em>
        to pass through, only an ever-receding approach. That rules out holding still, and it rules
        out going straight through. One option is left: go <em>around</em>. And going around needs
        nothing you can't have. You don't have to <em>be</em> at the center to circle it — you only
        have to keep it in relation to you and keep moving. Keep it on your left and keep going. The
        circling isn't a flourish on top of stability. Around a center you can never reach, circling
        is the only form persistence can take.
      </p>
      <p>
        One last move, and it's the strangest. Of all the places along that crossing, there is
        exactly <em>one</em> where the two sides stand in precisely the relation a finer world would
        need to hold together — and it is the one place that relation cannot be held as a world of
        its own. A single locus, set apart from every other: just what a frame requires, and unable
        to be one. And that locus, seen from close enough in, simply <em>is</em> an origin — with its
        own two sides, its own gradient, its own center that is never met. Which has its own, in
        turn.
      </p>
      <p>
        And here's where it turns personal. Accept that one premise — no smallest scale — and the
        nesting simply never bottoms out: inside every world is a finer one, with no end, no floor
        to reach. Go the other way and no frame wears a number that means anything absolute —
        <em>finer, coarser, first, last</em> are only names for where you happen to be standing. So
        every frame, seen from inside itself, is a ground: a finer world within it, a coarser world
        it sits inside, the same unreachable center at the heart of its own scale as at every other.
        No privileged rung. No view from any bottom — because inside is the only place there is to
        be. Wherever you look from, you're in the middle of it. The middle is everywhere.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- ============ Landing · name the shape ============ -->
    <section class="mb-16">
      <div class="themed-surface border rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
        <p class="text-lg" style="color: var(--color-text); line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);">
          <strong>Stable things persist by circulating around a center that is never met</strong> —
          and every such center, seen from close enough in, is itself the origin of a finer world
          that can never hold still as a world of its own.
        </p>
      </div>
      <p class="themed-text-muted">That's the pattern. Everything after this is just watching it turn up.</p>
    </section>

    <div class="themed-border border-t mb-16"></div>

    <!-- ============ 3 · Recognition cascade ============ -->
    <section class="mb-16">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">You've already seen it</h2>
      <p class="themed-text-secondary mb-10" style="line-height: var(--leading-prose);">
        You don't have to trust the logic. Once you have the shape, it's hard to stop finding it.
      </p>

      <div class="space-y-10">
        <div class="text-center">
          <div class="w-14 h-14 mx-auto mb-3" style="color: var(--color-surface-nav);"><Icon name="wheel" size="100%" /></div>
          <p class="themed-text-secondary" style="line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);">
            Thirty spokes, one empty hub. The wheel works because of what's absent — fill the hub
            and nothing turns.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="text-center">
          <div class="w-14 h-14 mx-auto mb-3" style="color: var(--color-deeper);"><Icon name="atom" size="100%" /></div>
          <p class="themed-text-secondary" style="line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);">
            Electrons never reach the nucleus and never escape it. They orbit — a center approached
            forever, never met.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="text-center">
          <div class="w-14 h-14 mx-auto mb-3" style="color: var(--color-lateral);"><Icon name="tree" size="100%" /></div>
          <p class="themed-text-secondary" style="line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);">
            A tree stands for centuries around a core that's often hollow; the only living layer is
            the thin skin at its edge. The middle is never where the life is.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="text-center">
          <div class="w-14 h-14 mx-auto mb-3" style="color: var(--color-surface-nav);"><Icon name="valley" size="100%" /></div>
          <p class="themed-text-secondary" style="line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);">
            A valley is lowest, so everything flows to it. It gathers by giving way — receiving at
            the one point it never has to reach for.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="themed-text-secondary mt-10" style="line-height: var(--leading-prose);">
        Your own heart doesn't beat and then rest — the beating-and-resting <em>is</em> the heart.
        A hurricane is enormous violence held around a still eye it never closes. You are not a
        thing sitting at a place. You're a pattern, circling.
      </p>
      <p class="themed-text-muted italic mt-6 text-center">
        The universe doesn't hold still. It circles centers it never reaches.
      </p>
    </section>

    <div class="themed-border border-t mb-16"></div>

    <!-- ============ 5 · The reveal ============ -->
    <section class="mb-16">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-6">And then, somewhere I didn't expect</h2>
      <div class="space-y-6 themed-text-secondary" style="line-height: var(--leading-prose);">
        <p>
          I didn't go looking for this in an old book. I built the whole thing from that one
          question about infinity, followed the logic, and watched it turn up in wheels and atoms
          and heartbeats. And then I reread something I'd read decades ago and found dry — the Dao
          De Jing — and its opening didn't read like mystical hedging. It read like a coordinate
          system. The recurring images — wheels, valleys, bellows, water — weren't decoration. They
          were the same demonstrations.
        </p>
        <p>
          I want to be honest about the direction of travel: I built the framework <em>through</em>
          that text, so its agreeing with me proves nothing — agreement with your own seed is
          exactly what you'd expect. It isn't evidence. It's the thing I'm translating. But watching
          a 2,500-year-old page line up, character by character, with something you reached from
          pure logic is — whatever else it is — a strange and good feeling.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <div class="themed-border border-t mb-16"></div>

    <!-- ============ 6 · The soft door ============ -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <p class="themed-text-secondary mb-8" style="line-height: var(--leading-prose);">
        I don't know if any of this is true. The whole thing hangs on one <em>if</em>, and I've
        tried to be honest that I can't prove it. What I can do is show you exactly how hard I've
        tried to break it.
      </p>
      <div class="space-y-3">
        <a href="/confidence" class="block themed-surface border rounded-lg p-4 transition-colors hover:opacity-80">
          <p class="font-semibold">How solid is this?</p>
          <p class="text-sm themed-text-muted">Every claim with its status — what's derived, what's still open.</p>
        </a>
        <a href="/claims" class="block themed-surface border rounded-lg p-4 transition-colors hover:opacity-80">
          <p class="font-semibold">What it claims, and what it doesn't</p>
          <p class="text-sm themed-text-muted">The boundary — and the predictions that could kill it.</p>
        </a>
        <a href="/docs/rsm/rosetta-stone" class="block themed-surface border rounded-lg p-4 transition-colors hover:opacity-80">
          <p class="font-semibold">The vocabulary, and the discipline that keeps it honest</p>
          <p class="text-sm themed-text-muted">How the same shape gets read across domains — without overclaiming.</p>
        </a>
      </div>
      <p class="themed-text-muted italic mt-10 text-center">Pattern, not proof. Not sealed.</p>
    </section>

  </article>
</BaseLayout>
